<div class="container">
    <h1>6. Common Selectors</h1>

    <p>Before exploring more complex CSS selectors, it's important to understand the most commonly used selectors today: <strong>type</strong>, <strong>class</strong>, and <strong>ID</strong>. These are the building blocks for targeting elements on your web page.</p>

    <h2>Selector Examples</h2>
    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">HTML</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            &lt;section id="intro"&gt;<br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;h1&gt;Welcome&lt;/h1&gt;<br>
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&lt;h2 class="tagline"&gt;Learn CSS Selectors&lt;/h2&gt;<br>
            &lt;/section&gt;
        </div>
    </div>

    <div class="code-container">
        <div class="code-header">CSS</div>
        <div class="code-content">
            h1 { font-size: 24px; color: #333; }<br>
            .tagline { font-style: italic; color: #555; }<br>
            #intro { padding: 20px; background-color: #f0f0f0; }
        </div>
    </div>

    <h2>Common Selectors Overview</h2>
    <table>
        <thead>
            <tr>
                <th>Example</th>
                <th>Selector Type</th>
                <th>Explanation</th>
            </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr>
                <td>h1</td>
                <td>Type Selector</td>
                <td>Targets elements by their HTML tag name.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>.tagline</td>
                <td>Class Selector</td>
                <td>Targets elements by their class attribute. Can be reused on multiple elements.</td>
            </tr>
            <tr>
                <td>#intro</td>
                <td>ID Selector</td>
                <td>Targets a single element by its unique ID. Should only appear once per page.</td>
            </tr>
        </tbody>
    </table>

